{"/service/ndnp/mthi/batch_mthi_beargrass_ver01/data/sn86075096/00340581702/1948110101/0919.xml":{"full_text":"Smoking- pleasure in\nDOUBLE MEASURE!\nYes! in pipes or in papers, there's more smoking joy with mild,\nrich-tasting Prince Albert \u2014America's largest-selling tobacco!\nT with pa/s\nl NSW HUMIDOR TOP\nPOCKET TIN, FIND 4\nTHE LAST PIPEFUL OF PA.\n/S AS RICH\nTASTING- AND\nCOOL SMOKING\nk AS THE FIRST!\n,p\nlisp\ni\nII\npi\nHi\nIII\nm\n\"In all the years I've been smoking a pipe,\" says Carl Hauck, \"I've\nfound no other tobacco like crimp cut P. A. for extra-tasty, tongue\neasy smoking joy. And the new Humidor Top on the pocket tin\nkeeps P. A. even fresher and more fiavorful than before.\"\n\u00a3\u00bb13\nTHE NEW HUMIDOR TOP locks IN the FRESHNESS and FLAVOR\nMORE MEN SMOKE\n[si\nPRIMEALBl\nTHAN ANY OTHER TOBACCO\n\n\n[9\nTHE NATIONAL JOY SMOKE J\nW THAT NEW H\nIT HUMIDOR TOP KEEPS\nEASY-TO-ROLL, CRIMP CUT\ny PRINCE ALBERT\nRICH TASTING AND A\nFRESH DOWN TO\nTHE BOTTOM OF\nTHE TIN A\nm\n\u25a0fi\n\n;Y;\nr i\n4>.:\nm\n\n\n\n\n\n#s|\n\"Crimp cut Prince Albert is my choice for fast, easy rolling of firm,\nneat cigarettes,\" says Eric Tinsley. \"I like the way P. A.'s crimp\ncut tobacco holds in the paper for easy shaping of extra-tasty,\nextra-mild, full-bodied 'makin's' smokes.\"\nK. J. Reynolds Tobacco Company, Winston-Salem, N. G.\n-K TUNE IN \"GRAND OLE OPRY\" Saturday Nights on N.B.C.\n4\u2014November 1, 1 9-4\u00d4\nKeeping in Touch With Washington\n5-Year Outlook Good\n2E\nWASHINGTON, D. C.\u2014Govern\nment economists are optimistic over\nthe prospects for agriculture during\nthe next five years.\nAssuming that a stable peace\nestablished, they think the\noutlook for farmers is pretty\nfavorable until 1954. That is as\nlong as they want to make pre\ndictions at the present time.\nPopulation is increasing at the\nrate of one to two million a year,\npeople are demanding more and\nbetter food and employment in the\ncities is expected to continue at\nfairly high levels.\nThe next five years could be as\nprosperous for everyone as any simi\nlar period in the past.\nWhile the economists look for ad\njustments in prices\u2014both farm and\nnon-farm prices\u2014no one looks for\neither to drop to depression levels.\nIf adjustments are relatively mild,\nwith little interruption to production,\nthe chances for an extended period\nof full employment are seen as very\ngood.\nAnd with full employment, there\nwould be a ready market for agri\ncultural products\u2014particularly the\nbetter types of food such as milk,\neggs, meat and poultry.\nEven in the case of a recession in\nemployment\u2014say 10 percent fewer\njobs\u2014total purchasing power would\nbe down only about 5 percent.\nPer capita buying power still\nwould be about one-third higher\nthan the five-year prewar period,\n1935 to 1939. The economists point\nout that wage rates have doubled\nsince 1939 and are relatively inflex\nible in business downturns.\nFarm prices have already begun to\nlevel off, but with production costs\ncontinuing to rise there will have to\nbe a leveling off here, too.\nBut there is optimism among con\ngressional farm leaders about the\nfuture relationship of farm prices.\nRepresentative Clifford Hope of\nKansas, chairman of the house agri\nculture committee, summed up his\nopinion the other day in these words.\nFarm prices, he said, will adjust\nis\nthemselves, \"not at war prices, not\nat depression prices, but at prices\nwhere the city people and the farm\npeople can do business with one an\nother.\"\nAs long as farm and city people\ncan do business with one another\u2014to\nthe advantage of both it means\nprosperity for both.\nAnd that is what the government\neconomists see as the prospects for\nthe next five years.\nLOWER FARM \"PAY\"\nIn the immediate futun\n1949\u2014the economists see the\npossibility of lower \"take home\npay\" for the farmer\u2014what he\nhas left from his gross receipts\nafter meeting production ex\npenses.\nIf production costs remain about\nthe same in 1949 as they now are,\nnet farm income next year probably\nwill be about 10 percent below 1948\ndue to an expected decrease in gross\nfarm income next year.\nObviously, this trend can't con\ntinue if there are to be five years\nof prosperity ahead.\nProduction costs must level off,\ntoo, and apparently the economists\nbelieve this is in the cards. Full em\nployment and full production in the\ncities and factories should have the\n-in\nsame effect as full production on the\nfarm\u2014a leveling off of prices.\nWhile an adjustment in prices\u2014\u2022\nboth farm and otherwisi\npated, no one looks for either to drop\nto depression levels.\nFarm prices are cushioned by the\ngovernment support programs. They\ncannot decline disproportionately be\nlow other prices. As other prices\ncome down, farm prices will come\ndown, too.\nThe presidential campaign has\ntended to dispel any suggestion that\ncongress will weaken this program\n\u2014which was wholeheartedly ac\ncepted by both parties.\n-is antici\nCOSTS MOUNTING\nFarmers already are beginning\nto feel the pinch of mounting\nproduction costs.\nThe expected decline in net in\ncome next year would be the first\ndecrease in this item in 10 years.\nThe bureau of agricultural eco\nnomics estimates 1948 gross farm in\ncome at $34,600,000,000. Production\nexpenses are estimated at $18,100,\n000,000. This leaves $16,500,000,000\nin net income, compared with $17,\n800,000,000 in 1947.\nFORSEE ACREAGE CUT\nA one-third cut in wheat acre\nage by 1954 is foreseen by agri\nculture department economists.\nThis would mean an acreage of\n55,000,000 acres by that time com\npared to the 79,000,000 expected to\nbe seeded for next year's crop.\nThe economists base their fore\ncasts on the belief that by 1954 the\nexport market will take only 150,\n000,000 bushels of American wheat.\nShipments abroad from last year's\ncrop set a record of 485,000,000 bush\nels and some officials in Washington\nbelieve exports from the 1948 crop\nwill be larger.\nIf acreage is reduced in the next\nfive years as the economists predict,\nit undoubtedly would involve gov\nernment planting and marketing\ncontrols.\nRECORD CORN CROP\nAf present prices, the value of\nthis year's record-shattering corn\ncrop is $6,300,000,000, or about\n2Vi times as much as the near\nrecord wheat crop, already har\nvested or about finished.\nThe crop is almost 10 percent\nhigher than the all-time record of\ntwo years ago, which department of\nagriculture experts forecasts at that\ntime wouldn't be excelled in years.\nFARM ELECTRIFICATION\nExtension of electricity to\nrural areas has opened a vast\nnew market for electrical house\nhold appliances.\nAnd if farm income continues\ngood\u2014that is, if the farmer has the\nmoney to spend, farm families in\nthe next year are likely again to\nspend a good share of it for electrical\nappliances.\nThis is the opinion of Dr. Gertrude\nS. Weiss, head, family economics\ndivision of USDA's bureau of hu\nman nutrition and home economics.\nMontana Farmer-Stockman\nPublished twice month, on the 1st and 15th,\nbj The Montana Parmer. Inc., Great Pall\u00bb,\nMont Entered as second class matter at the\nPostoffice at Great Palls. Mon\ntana. under act of March 3. 1879.","height":"15867","width":"11082"}}
